│ My previous fix attempted to solve the signed overflow by    │
│ returning a "full set" `ConstantRange`. However, this was    │
│ incorrect because `ConstantRangeList::insert` does not       │
│ support full sets, leading to a different assertion failure. │
│                                                              │
│ The correct way to handle this overflow is to recognize that │
│ we cannot represent the access range with a single           │
│ `ConstantRange`. In such cases, `GetConstantIntRange` should │
│ indicate failure by returning `std::nullopt`. This signals   │
│ to the caller that the access range is unknown or too        │
│ complex. The caller, `getArgumentAccessInfo`, will then      │
│ proceed with an empty `ConstantRangeList`, which is the      │
│ conservative behavior when the exact range cannot be         │
│ determined.                                                  │
│                                                              │
│ I will now modify `GetConstantIntRange` to return            │
│ `std::nullopt` upon detecting a signed overflow, instead of  │
│ a full set.                                                  │
